Group Project: How are an employee's distance from home to work and job involvement associated with the likelihood of their attrition?

Members: Jennifer Li, Allan Wang, Zihua Li, Emma Oh

I. Introduction

Commute time and attrition¶

Have you ever considered skipping work—or even quitting—due to a long commute? Bakker and Demerouti's (2007) Job Demands-Resources Model suggests that prolonged commutes drain energy, reducing recovery time and job satisfaction. Zhang et al. (2023) supported this idea with an empirical study, showing that longer commutes are significantly linked to lower job satisfaction (β=.0024, p<.01).

Job involvement and attrition¶

Despite commute time being an external obstacle, what motivates us to continue working? According to Self-Determination Theory (SDT), vocational satisfaction arises from meeting needs for competence and autonomy. Competence is the perceived ability to master work tasks, while autonomy involves the freedom to make meaningful decisions (Olafsen et al., 2017). Haivas et al. (2013) found that satisfying these needs through job engagement significantly reduces the intention to quit (β=-.56, p=.012 for autonomy; β=-.54, p=.016 for competence), suggesting that increased job involvement is linked to a lower intention to quit.

Research Question¶

In line with previous research, our project seeks to investigate the inferential research question:

"How are the distance from home to work (in kilometers) and job involvement of employees associated with their likelihood of their attrition?"

B. Methods: Plan

1. Feature selection

What are our variables?

Response Variable: Attrition (whether an employee has left the company)

Explanatory Variables:

  • JobInvolvement: Measure of employee involvement at work
    • 1 = Low, 2 = medium, 3 = high, 4 = very high
  • DistanceFromHome: Distance in kilometers from home to office.

Why did we select our variables

Job Involvement: We chose Job Involvement as a measure of autonomy in SDT as it provides insights into the level of autonomy an employee experiences at work without being too broad like Job Satisfaction, which might include factors (e.g., coworker relationships) not of interest.

Distance From Home: We chose Distance From Home because longer commutes may lead to employee burnout (e.g., being stuck in rush hour).

Forward stepwise regression

Before selecting Job Involvement and Distance From Home as our predictors, we used stepwise forward selection to ensure their significance. For a variable to be considered a quality predictor, it should have a significant p-value ($\alpha < 0.05$) in the model.

         OverTime = factor(OverTime, levels = c("No", "Yes")),

         Department = as.factor(Department),
         JobRole = as.factor(JobRole),
         MaritalStatus = as.factor(MaritalStatus),
         BusinessTravel = as.factor(BusinessTravel))


# perform forward selection using stepAIC w goal of finding significant predictors

# a. split the data into training and selection set (70:30)
set.seed(155)
hr_clean_2 <- 
    hr_clean_2 %>%
    mutate(id = row_number())

training_hr <- 
    hr_clean_2 %>%
    slice_sample(prop = 0.70, replace = FALSE)

selection_set_hr <- 
    hr_clean_2 %>%
    anti_join(training_hr, by = "id")

training_hr <- 
    training_hr %>% 
    select(-"id")

selection_set_hr <- 
    selection_set_hr %>% 
    select(-"id")

# b. perform stepwise forward selecton

base_model <- glm(Attrition ~ 1, data = selection_set_hr, family = binomial)
full_model <- glm(Attrition ~ ., data = selection_set_hr, family = binomial)

forward_model <- stepAIC(base_model, direction = "forward", scope = list(lower = base_model, upper = full_model), trace = FALSE)

# c. summary of the final selected model

2. What method did we choose?

Method: Logistic Regression:

To address how employee engagement (measured by JobInvolvement) and DistanceFromHome impact the likelihood of employees leaving the company, we use logistic regression as our analysis method. Logistic regression is suitable for this study because it handles a binary response variable and provides easily interpretable results.

Log Odds Form: $$\log\left(\frac{p}{1-p}\right) = \beta_0 + \beta_1X_{DistanceFromHome} + \beta_2X_{JobInvolvement2} + \beta_3X_{JobInvolvement3} + \beta_4X_{JobInvolvement4}$$

3. Fitting the Model

We fit the model to the hr_clean dataset using the glm function with family="binomial" to perform logistic regression. The coefficients are exponentiated, allowing interpretation as odds ratios.

Job Involvement - Dummy Variables

The categorical predictor JobInvolvement measures employee engagement on a scale of 1-4. Dummy variables are created, with level 1 as the reference. Our model includes three dummy variables:

\begin{equation} JobInvolvement_i = \left\{\begin{array}{lr} 1, & \text{if JobInvolvement}=i\\ 0, & \text{otherwise} \end{array}\right. \end{equation}

\begin{equation} \text{for}\quad i = 2,3,4 \end{equation}

Thus, we build the logistic regression model below.

  • Due to the scope of this class, we will not be checking for linearity explicitly. However, assessing linearity is crucial in practice because logistic regression assumes a linear relationship between predictors and the log-odds of the outcome, impacting the model’s accuracy and the validity of coefficient interpretations.

Coefficients Interpretation¶

  • $Intercept$: The baseline odds of attrition for employees with low job involvement and living zero kilometers from the office are approximately 0.313. This means for every 1 employee who leaves, about 3.19 employees stay ( 1/0.313≈3.19).

  • $DistanceFromHome$: Holding job involvement constant, each additional kilometer increase between employee's home and the office changes the odds of attrition by a factor of 1.028, or there is a 2.8% increase in the odds of leaving $(1.028−1≈2.8)$

  • $JobInvolvement_2$: Holding distance from home constant, medium job involvement changes the odds of attrition by a factor of 0.648 compared to low job involvement, or there is a 35.2% reduction in the odds of leaving $(1−0.648≈0.352)$.

  • $JobInvolvement_3$: Holding distance from home constant, high job involvement changes the odds of attrition by a factor of 0.426 compared to low job involvement, or there is a 57.4% reduction in the odds of leaving $(1−0.426≈0.574)$.

  • $JobInvolvement_4$: Holding distance from home constant, very high job involvement changes the odds of attrition by a factor of 0.290 compared to low job involvement, or there is a 71.0% reduction in the odds of leaving $(1−0.290≈0.71)$.

7. Model Inference

To investigate the association between Attrition and DistanceFromHome, and JobInvolvement, we perform hypothesis testing and evaluate the confidence intervals. Firstly, the hypothesis test performed for this study is as follows: \begin{gather*} H_0: \beta_j = 0\\ H_a: \beta_j \neq 0. \end{gather*} where $j=1,2,3,4$.

The wald’s statistic is: $$z_j = \frac{\hat{\beta}_j}{\mbox{SE}\left(\hat{\beta}_j\right)}$$

  • Under $H_0$ it approximately follows a standard normal distribution. Given the large sample size (1029 observations), this assumption is satisfied by the properties of maximum likelihood estimation and the Central Limit Theorem.

We perform hypothesis testing and interpret the p-values to determine the significance of each predictor variable in relation to the odds of Attrition.

Observed Results¶

With a large sample size, the confidence intervals provide stable and reliable estimates. Based on the results in Figure 14, we gather the following insights on the relationship between distance from home and job involvement on attrition using $\alpha = .05$

Coefficient Significance¶

  • $Intercept$: With a p-value ≈ 0, we reject $H_0$. We have sufficient evidence to suggest that the baseline odds ratio of attrition for employees with low job involvement living zero kilometers from the office are significant.

  • $DistanceFromHome$: With a p-value = 0.005, we reject $H_0$. We have sufficient evidence to conclude that distance from home is associated with the odds of attrition.

  • $JobInvolvement_2$ With a p-value = 0.180, we fail to reject $H_0$. We do not have sufficient evidence to conclude that medium job involvement is a significant predictor of attrition.

  • $JobInvolvement_3$ With a p-value = 0.005, we reject $H_0$. We have sufficient evidence to conclude that high job involvement is a significant predictor of attrition.

  • $JobInvolvement_4$ With p-value = 0.004, we reject $H_0$. We have sufficient evidence to conclude that very high job involvement is significantly associated with the odds of attrition

95% Confidence Intervals¶

  • $Intercept[0.168, 0.562]$: For employees with zero kilometers distance from home and low job involvement, we are 95% confident that the odds of attrition are between 0.168 and 0.562 times the average odds. This indicates a significantly lower likelihood of leaving compared to the average employee.

  • $DistanceFromHome [1.008, 1.047]$: We are 95% confident that, holding job involvement constant, each additional kilometer of distance from home for employees changes the odds of attrition by a factor of 1.008 to 1.047.

  • $JobInvolvement_2 [0.348, 1.243]$: We are 95% confident that, holding distance from home constant, medium job involvement changes the odds of attrition for employees by a factor ranging from 0.348 to 1.243 compared to low job involvement. However, this relationship is not statistically significant (p > .05).

  • $JobInvolvement_3 [0.237, 0.793]$: We are 95% confident that, holding distance from home constant, high job involvement changes the odds of attrition for employees by a factor of 0.237 to 0.793 compared to low job involvement.

  • $JobInvolvement_4 [0.122, 0.662]$: We are 95% confident that, holding distance from home constant, very high job involvement changes the odds of attrition for employees by a factor of 0.122 to 0.662 compared to low job involvement.

Observations¶

  • The lower AIC for the logit model indicates a better fit than the null model, suggesting that the predictors DistanceFromHome and JobInvolvement improve the model's ability to explain attrition with the training data. On the other hand, the higher BIC for the logit model indicates that despite the improved fit, the added complexity of the model may not be justified, as BIC imposes a stronger penalty for the number of parameters.

III. Discussion

Results and Implications¶

In line with our hypothesis and Zhang et al. (2023), we find a significant positive correlation between the distance from home to the workplace and the odds of attrition (p = .005 < .05). The farther employees live from their workplace, the more likely they are to quit. Similar to Haivas et al. (2013), we found that the effect of Job Involvement on the odds of attrition depends on the level of involvement. Employees with high/very high job involvement are significantly less likely to leave their jobs compared to those with a low job involvement level (the reference level), with the exception of medium job involvement.

Understanding these relationships have important implications for company management in reducing employee attrition:

  • Distance from home: Companies can consider options such as hybrid or remote work for employees who have long commutes.
  • Job involvement: Companies can boost job involvement by improving job autonomy and competence (Olafsen et al., 2017), such as offering career development opportunities, and giving employees more freedom in their routine.

Model Improvement¶

While our low AIC (compared to the null) suggests that the additional variables enhance the explanation of attrition, the higher BIC (compared to the null) indicates that this improvement may not justify the increased model complexity. To address the increase in BIC, we can identify factors contributing to unnecessary complexity:

  • Interaction Terms: Medium job involvement was not a significant predictor of attrition. Adding interaction terms between JobInvolvement and DistanceFromHome could reveal significant combined effects for some levels of job involvement (e.g., high and very high) but not for medium job involvement, justifying the model's complexity if the interactions are significant.
  • Nested Models: Start with a simpler model including only DistanceFromHome and significant levels of JobInvolvement, and compare their AIC and BIC metrics to the full model. This could help identify unnecessary predictors, potentially reducing BIC by simplifying the model.

Future Research Directions¶

Future research could incorporate psychological factors into our logistic model, such as employee job stress, perceived work-life balance, and marital status to gain a more comprehensive understanding of employee attrition.
